//347. Top K Frequent Elements
//Medium
//Topics
//premium lock icon
//Companies
//Given an integer array nums and an integer k, return the k most frequent elements. You may return the answer in any order.
//Example 1:
//Input: nums = [1,1,1,2,2,3], k = 2
//Output: [1,2]
//Example 2:
//Input: nums = [1], k = 1
//Output: [1]
//Example 3:
//Input: nums = [1,2,1,2,1,2,3,1,3,2], k = 2
//Output: [1,2]


Brute Force Approach ->
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> topKFrequent(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        unordered_map<int, int> freq;
        for(int num : nums) {
            freq[num]++;                 // For nums = [1,1,1,2,2,3], freq[1]++; , Since 1 is not in the map yet, C++ automatically creates: 1->0 then increments it.  
}
        vector<int> result;
        for(int i = 0; i < k; i++) {
            int maxFreq = 0;
            int element = 0;
            for(auto& pair : freq) {    //Already learned about this in previous code
                if(pair.second > maxFreq) {
                    maxFreq = pair.second;
                    element = pair.first;
                }
            }
            result.push_back(element);
            freq.erase(element);
        }
        return result;     // Max k elements from nums in results
    }
};

Complexity Analysis
Time Complexity -> O(n + k × m)
where:
n = size of nums
m = number of unique elements
Reason:
Building frequency map → O(n)
Finding maximum frequency k times → O(k × m)
Space Complexity -> O(m)
where:
m = number of unique elements


Optimal Approach (Bucket Sort)

class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> topKFrequent(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        unordered_map<int, int> freq;
        for(int num : nums) {
            freq[num]++;
        }
        vector<vector<int>> bucket(nums.size() + 1);                                     
//nums.size() = 6    , This is how bucket will look like bucket[0] = []
//                     bucket[1] = []
//                     bucket[2] = []
//                     bucket[3] = []
//                     bucket[4] = []
//                     bucket[5] = []
//                     bucket[6] = []
        for(auto& pair : freq) {                                                      // Example: 1 -> 3 means bucket[3].push_back(1)
            bucket[pair.second].push_back(pair.first);                                // 3 -> [1] ,Store the number in the bucket corresponding to its frequency.
        } 
        vector<int> result;
        for(int i = bucket.size() - 1; i >= 0 && result.size() < k; i--) {
            for(int num : bucket[i]) {
                result.push_back(num);
                if(result.size() == k) {
                    return result;
                }
            }
        }
        return result;        //(This won't ever execute), Read note at the last.
    } 
};


Complexity Analysis
Time Complexity -> O(n)
where:
n = size of nums
Reason:
Counting frequencies → O(n)
Filling buckets → O(n)
Traversing buckets → O(n)
Total: O(n)
Space Complexity -> O(n)
where:
n = size of nums
Reason:
#Hash map stores frequencies.
#Bucket array stores all unique elements.



Corner Cases
1. Single Element
nums = [1]
k = 1
Output:
[1]

2. All Elements Same
nums = [5,5,5,5]
k = 1
Output:
[5]

3. All Elements Unique
nums = [1,2,3,4]
k = 2
Output can be:
[1,2]
or
[3,4]
(any 2 elements, since all frequencies are equal)

4. k Equals Number of Unique Elements
nums = [1,1,2,2,3]
k = 3
Output:
[1,2,3]

5. Negative Numbers
nums = [-1,-1,-2,-2,-2]
k = 1
Output:
[-2]
Note:
The second return is there because of programming style / compiler safety.
Imagine we wrote a broken version:
nums = [1,1,1] k = 5
Frequency map: 1 -> 3
There is only 1 unique element, but we're asking for 5.
The loop would finish with: result = [1] and never reach: if(result.size() == k) because: 1 != 5
Then execution would fall through to: "return result;" at the bottom.
But that input is impossible according to the problem constraints.
